1. Data Model Philosophy

    MongoDB

        JSON-like documents
        Developer-friendly
        Easy to evolve schema


    Cassandra

        Wide-column (like distributed BigTable)
        Designed for huge write throughput


    DynamoDB

        Key-value + limited document
        Requires access-pattern-first design


    Cosmos DB

        Cosmos DB is a NoSQL document database.
        it stores data as JSON documents inside containers.
        It is schema-less and designed for global distribution.


2. Scaling & Performance

    MongoDB
        Scales via sharding
        Good but not as seamless as others


    Cassandra

        Linear scalability
        No single point of failure
        Handles massive write-heavy workloads


    DynamoDB

        Auto scaling
        Handles millions of requests/sec
        No infra management


    Cosmos DB

        Multi-region writes
        Low latency globally


3. Query Capability

      DB	          Query Power
    MongoDB	    Rich queries, aggregation
    Cassandra	Limited (no joins)
    DynamoDB	Very limited
    Cosmos DB	SQL-like (depends on API)


4. Consistency Models

    MongoDB → Strong consistency
    Cassandra → Tunable (eventual by default)
    DynamoDB → Eventual (default) + optional strong
    Cosmos DB → 5 levels (very flexible)




When to Use

    Use MongoDB

        Complex queries
        Fast development
        Flexible schema

        Example:
            CMS
            Product catalogs


    Use Cassandra

        Write-heavy systems
        Huge scale (TB–PB data)
        Distributed systems

        Example:
            Logs, IoT, messaging


    Use DynamoDB

        AWS ecosystem
        Predictable latency
        High traffic APIs

        Example:
            Session store
            Order systems at scale

    
    Use Cosmos DB
        Multi-region apps
        Global users
        Need flexible consistency

        Example:
            Global SaaS apps